  }), "\n  "), "\n    ")), mdx("p", null, "I love thinking about and designing computer interfaces, in code and in the\nphysical world. And I really love knobs, specifically infinite-scrolling with\nrotary encoders."), mdx("p", null, "Pursuant to my love of interfaces and knobs, I put together a three-knob\ninterface for my laptop, and I call it \u201CKnobs.\u201D"), mdx("h2", null, "Why knobs?"), mdx("p", null, "I was thinking about the touch-based inputs we use so often now. I really like\ntouch screens, but they miss out on some of the haptic satisfaction of bulkier,\nolder-style interfaces. I love old Hi-Fi audio equipment, because of its sense\nof purpose and ease of operation. I wanted to experiment with a heavier, more\ntangible interface for my computer."), mdx("p", null, "Knobs are cool because they can represent any linearly variable quantity, like\nvolume, brightness, intensity, or tone. Thy can also represent position, speed,\nor menu choices. I built this project to be as open-ended as possible, because I\ndidn\u2019t really know what I would use it for."), mdx("h2", null, "Functionality"), mdx("p", null, "I currently have the knobs controlling my window manager. One emulates alt +\ntab, for switching between open windows, and one emulates ctrl + alt + arrow,\nfor switching between workspaces. I haven\u2019t decided what the third should do,\nand I haven\u2019t yet used the shaft button for anything."), mdx("h2", null, "Technical implementation"), mdx("p", null, "Knobs is really simple: an Arduino Pro Micro knockoff is wired to three rotary\nencoders. It doesn\u2019t have enough interrupts to watch all three, so instead it\npolls each encoder as quickly as possible."), mdx("p", null, "The Arduino has a built-in USB stack, so it emulates a keyboard. It sends\nkeypresses when the encoders move, and those are mapped to window-manager\ncontrols on my laptop."), mdx("p", null, "The source code, for Arduino 1.0 or higher,\n", mdx("a", {
    parentName: "p",
    "href": "https://github.com/ottobonn/Knobs",
